[1] Cholera - Sudan
Date: Wed, 21 Jun 2006
From: Marianne Hopp <mjhopp12@yahoo.com>
Source: WHO Outbreak Reports [edited]
<http://www.who.int/csr/don/2006_06_21a/en/index.html>

Between 21 Apr and 18 Jun 2006, the Federal Ministry of Health (FMoH)
has reported a total of 2007 cases, including 77 deaths (case
fatality rate,CFR=3.8 percent) of acute watery diarrhea in 9 out of
15 states in northern Sudan. Of these cases 35.3 percent (CFR=4.9
percent) have occurred in Khartoum state, while 26 percent have
occurred in North Kordofan state. The remaining cases have occurred
in White Nile, South Darfur, South Kordofan, Kassala, Red Sea, Al
Gezira and River Nile.
The National Public Health Laboratory of the FMoH has confirmed the
isolation of _Vibrio cholerae_ O1 Inaba in 70 out of 139 stool
samples (50 percent) collected so far from these states.
Between 28 Jan and 14 Jun 2006, a total of 16 187 cases, including
476 deaths (CFR=3 percent) of acute watery diarrhea has been reported
in 8 out of 10 states in southern Sudan (see previous report).
_Vibrio cholerae_ O1 Inaba has been laboratory-confirmed in several
stool samples by African Medical and Research Foundation (AMREF)
laboratories in Nairobi.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[Previous reports have concentrated on cholera in southern Sudan.
Cases are clearly occurring in the north as well. A map showing of
states of Sudan can be found at:
<http://www.un.org/Depts/Cartographic/map/profile/sudan.pdf> - Mod.LL]
