[3] Cholera - Congo DR (North Kivu)
Date: Thu, 22 Jun 2006
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: African News Dimensions [edited]
<http://www.andnetwork.com/index?service=direct/0/Home/recent.titleStory&sp=l40418>

A cholera outbreak has hit Goma, the capital city of North Kivu
province in the eastern Democratic Republic of Congo with 14 cases
having been reported in the government forces garrisoned in the
region, the UN mission to the country said on Wed, 21 Jun 2006.
The 14 cases were reported in the 5th and 7th brigades of the
government forces, said a press officer of the UN mission, adding
that the officers and soldiers of the 2 brigades, as well as their
families were living in appalling health conditions and running out
of drinking water and medicine. The press officer said another
cholera outbreak had occurred in the region of Rutshuru, some 50 km
north of Goma, leading to 7 deaths in the ninth brigade of the
government forces.
Most of the 800 000 residents in Goma have been drinking the unclean
water of lake Kivu since Jan 2002 when a volcano eruption destroyed
the water-supply system in the city. Last Aug 2005, more than 800
cholera cases were reported in the 4th brigade of the DRC government
forces in Goma and 30 people died.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[A map of Congo DR showing the location of Goma in North Kivu in the
northeast part of the country can be found at:
<http://www.un.org/Depts/Cartographic/map/profile/drcongo.pdf> - Mod.LL]
